03411nmm a2200481Ia 9781789201178DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817892011787 a10.1515/97817892011782doi  a(DE-B1597)671612  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a338.4/77362309569409043qOCoLC222/eng/202311201 aVries, David De, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiamonds and War :bState, Capital, and Labor in British-Ruled Palestine /cDavid De Vries. 1aNew York ;aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (362 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aThe mining of diamonds, their trading mechanisms, their financial institutions, and, not least, their cultural expressions as luxury items have engaged the work of historians, economists, social scientists, and international relations experts. Based on previously unexamined historical documents found in archives in Belgium, England, Israel, the Netherlands, and the United States, this book is the first in English to tell the story of the formation of one of the world's main strongholds of diamond production and trade in Palestine during the 1930s and 1940s. The history of the diamond-cutting industry, characterized by a long-standing Jewish presence, is discussed as a social history embedded in the international political economy of its times; the genesis of the industry in Palestine is placed on a broad continuum within the geographic and economic dislocations of Dutch, Belgian, and German diamond-cutting centers. In providing a micro-historical and interdisciplinary perspective, the story of the diamond industry in Mandate Palestine proposes a more nuanced picture of the uncritical approach to the strict boundaries of ethnic-based occupational communities. This book unravels the Middle-eastern pattern of state intervention in the empowerment of private capital and recasts this craft culture's inseparability from international politics during a period of war and transformation of empire.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781789201178?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781789201178zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781789201178/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA